         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (he thought): “the sensual pleasures [are] not permanent ones, nor [is] happiness everlasting ... [37d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #a7 #a8 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6 #b7 #b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1949"/><citedRange>II, 12-14</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>725</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>493</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (for everybody) must leave his people, but by no means will he obtain great fruit out of such abandonment. [38b] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(But whosoever) (goes) from the house, from such abandonment he will obtain great fruit [and] eternal happiness. [38d] The crude sensual pleasures ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>270</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1977"/><citedRange>112</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">in their smell those dignified ones, who have gone from the pool of sensual pleasures, [are] not to those ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>111</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>205</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the fire (of sensual pleasure) glows in [his] mind, the whole body burns on him like a firebrand with passion [39d] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Das Feuer (der Sinneslust) glüht in [seinem] Geist, der ganze Körper brennt ihm wie ein Feuerbrand(?) vor Leidenschaft.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">The fire (of sensual pleasure) glows in [his] mind, his whole body burns like a firebrand with passion.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>108</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>434</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>451</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">from (smell) [and] taste, from suffering and sorrow and from the two [sexual] kinds female and male he drives out all attachment. [40b] To whom, however, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1977"/><citedRange>112</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979b"/><citedRange>54</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">after (that about the sensual pleasures) he spoke this section about thirst. Hear this now with love! [40d] In Dharmasomas (Udānālaṅkāra) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the God (of Gods), the Buddha, the shelter and refuge, was staying near Śrāvastī. There he summoned the pupils ... [1b] ..</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Der Gott der (Götter), der Buddha, der Schutz [und] die Zuflucht, befand sich bei Śrāvastī. Dort rief er die Schüler ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">The god of (gods), the Buddha, the shelter [and] the protection, tarried near Śrāvastī. There he summoned the students ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>379</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(The thoughts) [are] to be held from the mind. (1). [To] such minded people this ripe fruit of thought [2a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>71</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">.... here at the demand of the (teachers). [2c] All this [is] wrong. Into judgments the beings turn the thoughts [2d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(In) this one’s (mind) are three thoughts: one of sensual pleasures, the second, however, of malice, the third that of harm [3c] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(In) diesem (Geist) wirken drei Vorstellungen: eine der Sinneslust, die zweite aber des Übelwollens, die dritte die des Leidzufügens.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">(Within) this (spirit) three notions operate: one of sensuality, the second of ill will, the third the one of inflicting suffering.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>280</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">.... not from the Yakṣas. [4a] As it [is] the peculiarity of this one’s mind, by the liquor of the thoughts he [is] (intoxicated?) [4b]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>174</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the evil flaws of the thoughts, of these beware. [4d] Then the Buddha spoke (two strophes) ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... die üblen Fehler der Vorstellungen, vor denen hütet euch!</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... the evil flaws of the imaginations, of these beware!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>84, 306</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1987"/><citedRange>187</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(When) the thoughtful (human, aroused by the thoughts), a being of violent passion, [is] seeing (only) the purity of this body, [then] his thirst (grows) even more ... [5d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969a"/><citedRange>320</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If he is (anxious for the smothering of the thoughts, however), constantly practices a disgust [at the body], [is] constantly mindful [and] controlling all six senses in, ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[Wenn] er ... ständig das Abscheu-Empfinden [gegenüber dem Körper] übt, ständig bedachtsam [und] alle sechs Sinnesfunktionen im Zaum haltend[wtl. gezügelt habend] [ist], ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">[If] he ... at all times practices the feeling of disgust [with regard to the body], [when he is] at all times deliberate [and] keeping all six sensory functions in check [lit. having disciplined], ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>351</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>76</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Buddha. [6d] Who, however, were still beginners, they/who ... the evil thoughts ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">Uv 2 colophon-3.2</note><note type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">On the recto side down to line 7 this contains the ending of part 2 of the Kāmavarga (II), i.e. strophes 37d-40 in a 4x25 syllable-metre (rhythm: 5/5/8/7). In line 8 the Tṛṣṇāvarga (III) begins, strophes 1-7c, in a 4x18 metre (rhythm: 7/7/4).</note><note type="remarks">The original manuscript is missing, but was a piece of leaf patched together from various fragments, about the left half of leaf 41. In places the writing was attrited strongly, particularly in the top part.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendation according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="lingcomment"><hi>tsatkwaṃ</hi> for <hi>tsatkuṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendation according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendations according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="lingcomment"><hi>astarñe</hi> for <hi>astaräññe</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendations according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendations according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl>.</note></p>
         </div>
         <div type="parallel_texts">
            <head>Sanskrit parallel</head>
            <p><ref type="ms" target="#a4"/> corresponds to Uv. II, 4: 
madhurāgrā vipāke tu kaṭukā hy abhinanditāḥ 
kāmā dahanti vai bālān ulkevāmuñcataḥ karam</p>
            <p>At first sweet, but bitter in their maturity desires burn the madman, as a torch burns the hand, if it is not relinquished.</p>
            <p><ref type="ms" target="#b6"/> corresponds to Uv. III, 1: 
vitarkapramathitasya jantunas tīvra rāgasya śubhānudarśinaḥ 
bhūyas tṛṣṇā pravardhate gāḍhaṃ hy eṣa karoti bandhanam</p>
            <p>In a man driven mad by doubt, given over to violent passions, avid for happiness, carvings ceaselessly increase; he creates a bond for himself.</p>
            <p><ref type="ms" target="#b7"/> corresponds to Uv. III, 2: 
vitarkavyupaśame tu yo rato hy aśubhaṃ bhāvayate sadā smṛtaḥ 
tṛṣṇā hy eṣa prahāsyate sa tu khalu pūtikaroti bandhanam</p>
            <p>But he who delights in appeasing doubt, who thinks only of suffering, ever aware, he will escape craving; he, most certainly, causes his rotting bond to fall away.</p>
         </div>
