               <item n="m_parallelcomment_old">&lt;h3&gt;Sanskrit parallel&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a4.&lt;/b&gt; corresponds to Uv. II, 4:&lt;br&gt;
madhurāgrā vipāke tu kaṭukā hy abhinanditāḥ&lt;br&gt;
kāmā dahanti vai bālān ulkevāmuñcataḥ karam&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At first sweet, but bitter in their maturity desires burn the madman, as a torch burns the hand, if it is not relinquished.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b6.&lt;/b&gt; corresponds to Uv. III, 1:&lt;br&gt;
vitarkapramathitasya jantunas tīvra rāgasya śubhānudarśinaḥ&lt;br&gt;
bhūyas tṛṣṇā pravardhate gāḍhaṃ hy eṣa karoti bandhanam&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In a man driven mad by doubt, given over to violent passions, avid for happiness, carvings ceaselessly increase; he creates a bond for himself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b7.&lt;/b&gt; corresponds to Uv. III, 2:&lt;br&gt;
vitarkavyupaśame tu yo rato hy aśubhaṃ bhāvayate sadā smṛtaḥ&lt;br&gt;
tṛṣṇā hy eṣa prahāsyate sa tu khalu pūtikaroti bandhanam&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But he who delights in appeasing doubt, who thinks only of suffering, ever aware, he will escape craving; he, most certainly, causes his rotting bond to fall away.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
